<section class="card">
  <h2>About Peppers</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Heat-dependent warm-season crop—requires strong seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Peppers are frost-tender and can be killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), pepper viability depends on three constraints: planting after last frost, accumulating sufficient Growing Degree Days (GDD), and maturing fruit before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Compared to tomatoes, peppers require a longer heat runway and are more sensitive to cool nights.
    In short seasons, early indoor starts and variety selection are critical for preserving risk margin.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 8–10 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> 2–4 weeks after last frost (once nights are consistently warm)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 60–100 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline planning ranges. Night temperature stability strongly influences early growth speed.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~65°F (18°C) preferred</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–90°F (21–32°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Peppers stall easily in cool soil and cold nights.
    Early transplanting into marginal temperatures often delays flowering and reduces maturity buffer.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For a reminder of how frost dates function as climate normals (not forecasts), see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50), depending on type (sweet vs hot)</p>

  <p>
    Peppers are strongly heat-dependent. Even when labeled as “70-day” varieties, weak heat accumulation can extend time-to-harvest significantly.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the full frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most pepper varieties require <strong>60–100 frost-free days</strong> to reach harvest.
    However, maturity timing is highly sensitive to seasonal heat strength.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler climates, even when frost-free days appear sufficient on paper, weak GDD accumulation can delay ripening until very near first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Only with early varieties and strong heat accumulation</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Often, unless summer heat is reliable</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful (row cover, black mulch to increase heat)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Peppers have no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end production immediately.
    First frost is therefore a hard seasonal boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Start indoors early (8–10 weeks before transplant window)</li>
    <li>Wait for warm nights before transplanting</li>
    <li>Select early-maturing or compact varieties</li>
    <li>Use full sun and heat-retaining surfaces to increase effective GDD</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, pepper viability depends on whether your frost-free window and seasonal heat budget together exceed the crop’s maturity requirement.
    When buffer is thin, delayed transplanting or weak early heat often causes harvest to drift too close to first frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can peppers survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Peppers are frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why are my peppers not ripening?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, seasonal heat accumulation (GDD) is insufficient or early growth was slowed by cool conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>Are peppers harder than tomatoes in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Often yes. Peppers generally require more consistent warmth and may need a longer heat runway to mature reliably.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Peppers are highly heat-dependent and frost-sensitive.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 60–100 days, ~1,200–1,800+ GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>